Abstract

We introduce robust principal component analysis from a data matrix in which the entries of its columns have been corrupted by permutations, termed Unlabeled Principal Component Analysis (UPCA). Using algebraic geometry, we establish that UPCA is a well-defined algebraic problem in the sense that the only matrices of minimal rank that agree with the given data are row-permutations of the ground-truth matrix, arising as the unique solutions of a polynomial system of equations. Further, we propose an efficient two-stage algorithmic pipeline for UPCA suitable for the practically relevant case where only a fraction of the data have been permuted. Stage-I employs outlier-robust PCA methods to estimate the ground-truth column-space. Equipped with the column-space, Stage-II applies recent methods for unlabeled sensing to restore the permuted data. Allowing for missing entries on top of permutations in UPCA leads to the problem of unlabeled matrix completion, for which we derive theory and algorithms of similar flavor. Experiments on synthetic data, face images, educational and medical records reveal the potential of our algorithms for applications such as data privatization and record linkage.

1.1 Related Work

In this section, we briefly review some existing work on three problems that interconnect in this paper; that is, unlabeled sensing, robust principal component analysis with outliers, and matrix completion with outliers. Beyond them, we also mention the recent and related works of Breiding etÂ al. (2018, 2023) and Tachella etÂ al. (2023), that combine flavors from data science, inverse problems, and algebraic models.

1.1.1 Unlabeled Sensing

There is a large literature on application-specific problems that involve lack of correspondences, e.g. in computer vision or statistics; here we just review four recent methods for unlabeled sensing (Unnikrishnan etÂ al., 2018) that will be used in this paper. Recall that in unlabeled sensing one is given a subspace Sâˆ—âŠ‚â„msuperscriptğ‘†superscriptâ„ğ‘šS^{*}\subset\mathbb{R}^{m} of dimension rğ‘Ÿr and a point x~~ğ‘¥\tilde{x} which is some permuted version of a point xâˆ—âˆˆSâˆ—superscriptğ‘¥superscriptğ‘†x^{*}\in S^{*} and the goal is to recover xâˆ—superscriptğ‘¥x^{*} from Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} and x~~ğ‘¥\tilde{x}. A critical distinction among methods in the literature is the sparsity level Î±ğ›¼\alpha of the permutation, that is the ratio of coordinates that are moved by the permutation.

The case of dense permutations (Î±=1ğ›¼1\alpha=1) is extremely challenging, with existing methods only able to handle small ranks rğ‘Ÿr. We consider two methods known to perform best in this regime. The algebraic-geometric method called AIEM in Tsakiris etÂ al. (2020) has linear complexity in mğ‘šm, and instead concentrates its effort on solving a polynomial system of rğ‘Ÿr equations in rğ‘Ÿr variables to produce an initialization for an expectation maximization algorithm. Currently, this method is efficient for râ‰¤5ğ‘Ÿ5r\leq 5 and intractable otherwise. A very different method is CCV-Min of Peng and Tsakiris (2020), which proceeds via branch-and-bound together with concave minimization and can handle râ‰¤8ğ‘Ÿ8r\leq 8, though intractable otherwise. For a picture regarding the computational complexity of existing unlabeled sensing methods, we refer to the discussion in Peng and Tsakiris (2020).

For sparse permutations (small Î±ğ›¼\alpha) we review two methods (Slawski and Ben-David, 2019; Slawski etÂ al., 2021). The â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}-RR algorithm of Slawski and Ben-David (2019) applies an â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1} robust linear regression relaxation and it works when Î±â‰¤0.5ğ›¼0.5\alpha\leq 0.5. Another approach is the Pseudo-Likelihood method (PL) of Slawski etÂ al. (2021), which fits a two-component mixture density for each entry of x~~ğ‘¥\tilde{x}, one accounting for fixed data and the other for permuted data. The fitting is done via a combination of hypothesis testing, reweighted least-squares, and alternating minimization; while this method works well for Î±â‰¤0.7ğ›¼0.7\alpha\leq 0.7, it is sensitive to the particular basis of Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} used to generate x~~ğ‘¥\tilde{x}.

The unlabeled sensing problem has in fact been explored, at least theoretically, towards greater generality (Unnikrishnan etÂ al., 2015, 2018; Dokmanic, 2019; Tsakiris and Peng, 2019; Peng and Tsakiris, 2021; Tsakiris, 2023b). In one such extended setting, already present in (Unnikrishnan etÂ al., 2015, 2018), we are only given a subset of coordinates of x~~ğ‘¥\tilde{x} (and the subspace Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}) and we aim to recover xâˆ—superscriptğ‘¥x^{*}. We call this problem unlabeled sensing with missing entries. It is a more challenging problem for which very few algorithms exist; e.g. see Elhami etÂ al. (2017); Tsakiris and Peng (2019). Tsakiris and Peng (2019) proposes two algorithms: Algorithm-A is based on a combination of branch-and-bound and a dynamic programming strategy; Algorithm-B is a RANSAC-style method based also on dynamic programming computation. Both algorithms perform well, if the subspace dimension rğ‘Ÿr is sufficiently small (e.g., â‰¤3absent3\leq 3) and if one is given sufficiently many entries of x~~ğ‘¥\tilde{x}.

1.1.2 Robust PCA with Outliers

PCA methods with robustness to outliers will also play a role in this paper. Among a large literature we review four state-of-the-art methods inspired by sparse (You etÂ al., 2017), cosparse (Tsakiris and Vidal, 2018b) and low-rank (Xu etÂ al., 2012) (Rahmani and Atia, 2017) representations. In that context, X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} can be partitioned into inlier points that lie in an unknown rğ‘Ÿr-dimensional subspace Sâˆ—âŠ‚â„msuperscriptğ‘†superscriptâ„ğ‘šS^{*}\subset\mathbb{R}^{m} and outlier points that lie away from Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}; the goal is to recover Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} from X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}.

A successor of Soltanolkotabi and Candes (2012), the convex method of You etÂ al. (2017), which we refer to as Self-Expr, solves a self-expressive elastic net problem so that each x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j} is expressed as an â„“2subscriptâ„“2\ell_{2}-regularized sparse linear combination of the other points. Inlier points need approximately rğ‘Ÿr other inliers for their self-expression as opposed to about mğ‘šm points for outliers. The self-expressive coefficients are used to define transition probabilities of a random walk on the self-representation graph and the average of the tğ‘¡t-step transition probability distributions for t=1,â€¦,Tğ‘¡1â€¦ğ‘‡t=1,\dots,T is used as a score for inliers vs outliers, with higher scores expected for the former. Then S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} is taken to be the subspace spanned by the rğ‘Ÿr top x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j}â€™s.

Dual Principal Component Pursuit (DPCP) of Tsakiris and Vidal (2015, 2018b) solves a non-smooth non-convex problem for an orthonormal basis Bâˆ—superscriptğµB^{*} of the orthogonal complement of Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}. In contrast to other robust-PCA methods, particularly those based on convex optimization, DPCP was shown in Zhu etÂ al. (2018); Ding etÂ al. (2021) to tolerate as many outliers as the square of the number of inliers, under a relative spherically uniform distribution assumption on inliers and outliers. This assumption is certainly not true for outliers obtained by permuting the coordinates of inliers, but we will experimentally see that an even stronger property holds for the case of UPCA (Figure 5t).

The now classical outlier pursuit method of Xu etÂ al. (2012), which we refer to as OP, decomposes via convex optimization X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} into the sum of a low-rank matrix, representing the inliers, and a column-sparse matrix, representing the outliers. S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} is obtained as the rğ‘Ÿrth principal component subspace of the low-rank part. Finally, the Coherence Pursuit (CoP) method of Rahmani and Atia (2017) is based on the following simple but effective principle: with X~âˆ’jsubscript~ğ‘‹ğ‘—\tilde{X}_{-j} the matrix X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} with column jğ‘—j removed, for each x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j} one computes its coherence X~âˆ’jâŠ¤â€‹x~jsubscriptsuperscript~ğ‘‹topğ‘—subscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{X}^{\top}_{-j}\tilde{x}_{j} with the rest of the points. As it turns out, inliers tend to have coherences of higher â„“2subscriptâ„“2\ell_{2}-norm than outliers, and the rğ‘Ÿr top x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j}â€™s are taken to span S^^ğ‘†\hat{S}.

1.1.3 Matrix Completion with Outliers

As mentioned in the introduction, matrix completion â€” or robust PCA with missing entries â€” has been a well-studied problem, with numerous developed theories (CandÃ¨s and Recht, 2009; Candes and Plan, 2010; Singer and Cucuringu, 2010; Eriksson etÂ al., 2012; Balcan etÂ al., 2019; Tsakiris, 2023c) and algorithms (Cai etÂ al., 2010; Keshavan etÂ al., 2010; Balzano etÂ al., 2010; Majumdar and Ward, 2011; Tanner and Wei, 2013; Bertsimas and Li, 2020); see, e.g., Davenport and Romberg (2016); Vaswani and Narayanamurthy (2018) for a survey.

Closely related to this paper is a more general setting of matrix completion, where the given data matrix X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} not only has some entries missing but also some of its columns are outliers. This setup is more challenging, and research on it is relatively scarce. Chen etÂ al. (2011, 2015) considered this problem, and proposed a convex program that minimizes a combination of a nuclear norm with an â„“1,2subscriptâ„“12\ell_{1,2} norm over a matrix of variables. Their method, which we call MCO, is shown to succeed for sufficiently many inliers and observed entries. We will make use of MCO later, to solve our unlabeled matrix completion problem.

1.2 Contributions

In this paper, we consider the recovery of Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} from its unlabeled version X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}, which we term Unlabeled Principal Component Analysis (UPCA). We take one step further and generalize UPCA into Unlabeled Matrix Completion (UMC), where we now need to recover Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} from only a subset of entries of X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}. We make contributions in the following three aspects:

Theoretical contributions (Section 2)
  1. 1.

    We establish that as long as r:=rankâ¡(Xâˆ—)<minâ¡{m,n}assignğ‘Ÿranksuperscriptğ‘‹ğ‘šğ‘›r:=\operatorname{rank}(X^{*})<\min\{m,n\} and Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} is generic (see Definition 1), then up to a permutation of its rows, Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} is the only matrix of rank less than or equal to rğ‘Ÿr that is compatible with X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}. This asserts that UPCA is a well-posed problem, since the inherent ambiguity of whether X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} comes from Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} or a row-permuted version of Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} is in most cases practically harmless (Sections 2.1.1 and 2.1.3).

  2. 2.

    We establish that in this basic formulation, UPCA is a purely algebraic problem, by exhibiting a polynomial system of equations parametrized by X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}, whose solutions are all the row-permutations of Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*}; solving the UPCA problem amounts to obtaining one such solution (Section 2.1.4).

  3. 3.

    We furthermore generalize our UPCA theorems for UMC, thereby obtaining results of similar â€œinformation-theoreticalâ€ flavor for the scenario with permuted incomplete data (Section 2.2).

Algorithmic contributions (Section 3)
  1. 1.

    Inasmuch as solving the polynomial system of UPCA is in principle NP-hard, we introduce an efficient algorithmic pipeline, Algorithm 1, for the practically relevant case where a significant part of the data have undergone the same dominant permutation, while the rest of the points have been permuted arbitrarily (see Section 2.1.5); in the case of record linkage this would correspond to one of the records having much larger size than the others. The first stage of the pipeline employs PCA methods with robustness to outliers (Xu etÂ al., 2012; Soltanolkotabi and Candes, 2012; Rahmani and Atia, 2017; You etÂ al., 2017; Tsakiris and Vidal, 2018b; Zhu etÂ al., 2018; Lerman and Maunu, 2018) to produce an estimate S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} of Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} from X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}; the second stage of the pipeline uses unlabeled sensing methods (Slawski and Ben-David, 2019; Slawski etÂ al., 2021; Tsakiris etÂ al., 2020; Peng and Tsakiris, 2020) to furnish an estimate X^^ğ‘‹\hat{X} of Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} from S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} and X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} (See Algorithm 1). Moreover, we introduce a simple but efficient algorithm for unlabeled sensing, Algorithm 2, based on least-squares with recursive filtration.

  2. 2.

    Our algorithmic development for UMC is parallel to that of UPCA. We start with the dominant permutation assumption and introduce a two-stage algorithmic pipeline (Algorithm 3). The first stage detects and completes inlier columns, and then estimates the subspace Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} by matrix completion with column outliers (recall Section 1.1.3). The second stage estimates the data matrix Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} by solving the problem of unlabeled sensing on the projected coordinates for each column.

Experimental evaluation (Section 4)
  1. 1.

    We assess our algorithmic pipeline for UPCA and our proposed unlabeled sensing algorithm on synthetic data (Section 4.1.1 and 4.1.2), face images (Section 4.1.3), educational and medical records (Section 4.1.4), with encouraging results.

  2. 2.

    We also perform experiments for the proposed UMC pipeline (Section 4.2).

2 Theoretical Foundations

In this section, we formulate and study two problems, unlabeled principal component analysis (UPCA) and unlabeled matrix completion (UMC). The goal of UPCA is to recover a ground-truth rank-deficient matrix Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} from its unlabeled version X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}. The goal of UMC is to also recover Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*} from X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}, but now X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} is a partial observation of a permuted version of Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*}. See Figure 1 for an intuitive understanding of the setup; we will formalize the settings soon.

2.1.2 Elements of Algebraic Geometry

Before stating our results, we make the notion of generic precise using some basic algebraic geometry (Cox etÂ al., 2013; Harris, 1992). since rankâ¡Xâ‰¤rrankğ‘‹ğ‘Ÿ\operatorname{rank}X\leq r if and only if all (r+1)Ã—(r+1)ğ‘Ÿ1ğ‘Ÿ1(r+1)\times(r+1) determinants of Xğ‘‹X are zero.

The algebraic variety â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} admits a topology, called Zariski topology, which makes it convenient to work with. The closed sets in this topology are the algebraic subvarieties of â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r}. These are sets of matrices of rank â‰¤rabsentğ‘Ÿ\leq r, which in addition satisfy certain other polynomial equations in â„â€‹[Z]â„delimited-[]ğ‘\mathbb{R}[Z]. For example, the set of matrices of rank at most râˆ’1ğ‘Ÿ1r-1 is a proper closed subset of â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r}, because in addition to the equations defining â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r}, it is further defined by requiring all rÃ—rğ‘Ÿğ‘Ÿr\times r determinants to be zero. Open sets in â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} are defined as complements of closed sets, or equivalently they are defined by requiring that certain sets of polynomials are not all simultaneously zero. For example, the set of matrices of rank exactly equal to rğ‘Ÿr is a proper open subset of â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} defined by the non-simultaneous vanishing of all rÃ—rğ‘Ÿğ‘Ÿr\times r determinants of Zğ‘Z; a matrix has rank rğ‘Ÿr if and only if all (r+1)Ã—(r+1)ğ‘Ÿ1ğ‘Ÿ1(r+1)\times(r+1) determinants are zero and least one rÃ—rğ‘Ÿğ‘Ÿr\times r determinant is non-zero. Now, the algebraic variety â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} is irreducible in the sense that it can not be described as the union of two proper algebraic subvarieties of it (Kleiman and Landolfi, 1971). A consequence of this is that non-empty open sets of â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} have the very important property of being topologically dense. This means that given a non-empty open set ğ’°âŠ‚â„³rğ’°subscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{U}\subset\mathcal{M}_{r} and a point Xâˆˆâ„³rğ‘‹subscriptâ„³ğ‘ŸX\in\mathcal{M}_{r}, every neighborhood of Xğ‘‹X intersects ğ’°ğ’°\mathcal{U}. It follows that under any non-degenerate continuous probability measure on â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r}, a non-empty Zariski-open set of â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} has measure 111. For example, the set of matrices in â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} of rank rğ‘Ÿr is non-empty and open, and thus it is dense. Hence a randomly sampled matrix in â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} under a continuous probability measure will have rank rğ‘Ÿr with probability 111. We refer to such a fact by saying that a generic matrix in â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} has rank rğ‘Ÿr. More generally:

Definition 1

We say that a generic matrix in â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r} satisfies a property, if the property is true for every matrix in a non-empty open subset of â„³rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘Ÿ\mathcal{M}_{r}.

3 Algorithms

In this section, we study the problems of UPCA and UMC under the dominant identity permutation assumption. We propose two-stage algorithmic pipelines for both problems:

  • â€¢

    For UPCA, the first stage computes a subspace S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} from X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} via outlier-robust PCA methods. The second stage applies unlabeled sensing methods to X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} (and S^^ğ‘†\hat{S}) in a column-wise manner. Figure 4a gives a diagram, and Section 3.1 gives full details.

  • â€¢

    The UMC pipeline parallels and extends that of UPCA. The first stage computes S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} from X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} via matrix completion with column outliers. 3.1 Two-Stage Algorithmic Pipeline for UPCA

We saw in the previous section that the UPCA problem (2) is well-defined (Theorem 2) and in principle solvable by a polynomial system of equations (Theorem 3). However, this polynomial system is at the moment intractable to solve even for moderate dimensions. On the other hand, Theorem 4 suggests the following practical two-stage algorithmic pipeline for the case where there is a dominant permutation, which we will take to be the identity.

Stage-I of UPCA

The existence of a dominant identity permutation enables estimating the underlying subspace, which is the task of Stage-I in the proposed algorithmic pipeline. Hence, at Stage-I a PCA method with robustness to outliers is employed to produce an estimate S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} of Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} from X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X}. Such robust PCA methods include OP (Xu etÂ al., 2012), Self-Repr (Soltanolkotabi and Candes, 2012; You etÂ al., 2017), CoP (Rahmani and Atia, 2017), and DPCP (Tsakiris and Vidal, 2018b; Zhu etÂ al., 2018; Lerman and Maunu, 2018), as mentioned in Section 1.1.2.

Once equipped with a robust estimate of Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}, the aim of Stage-II is to estimate Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*}, which can be achieved by employing methods for unlabeled sensing. Hence, at Stage-II of the pipeline, one feeds S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} and X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} to an unlabeled sensing method (Slawski and Ben-David, 2019; Slawski etÂ al., 2021; Tsakiris etÂ al., 2020; Peng and Tsakiris, 2020; Mazumder and Wang, 2023; Onaran and Villar, 2022a), which operates point by point, returning for every x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j} an estimate x^jsubscript^ğ‘¥ğ‘—\hat{x}_{j}. Here one may choose to threshold the x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j}â€™s based on their distance to S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} and apply unlabeled sensing on the outliers only. Alternatively, if extra computational power is available for dispensing with choosing a threshold, one may apply unlabeled sensing on every x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j}; we follow this approach in the experiments for UPCA.

This proposed two-stage method is summarized in Algorithm 1.

A New Method For Unlabeled Sensing: LSRF

Inasmuch as there are very few scalable unlabeled sensing methods, we here propose a simple but comparatively efficient alternative named Least-Squares with Recursive Filtration (LSRF), see Algorithm 2. This method is parameter-free and alternates between ordinary least-squares and a dimensionality reduction step that removes the coordinate of the ambient space on which the residual error attains its maximal value, until rğ‘Ÿr coordinates are left. The complexity of LSRE is ğ’ªâ€‹(m2â€‹r2)ğ’ªsuperscriptğ‘š2superscriptğ‘Ÿ2\mathcal{O}(m^{2}r^{2}).

3.2 Two-Stage Algorithmic Pipeline for UMC

As in UPCA, we propose a two-stage pipeline for UMC that can be effective under the dominant permutation assumption. We detail our algorithmic pipeline next.

Stage-I of UMC

Stage-I of UMC parallels that of UPCA, with the same goal of estimating the ground-truth subspace Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}, yet with the additional challenge that the data matrix now has missing entries (Figure 1). Recall that, under the dominant permutation assumption, we can treat the columns permuted by the dominant permutation as inliers and others outliers (Figure 3). As such, Stage-I amounts to solving the problem of matrix completion with column outliers (reviewed in Section 1.1.3). To do so, a direct solution is employing the convex program of Chen etÂ al. (2015), called MCO, which estimates Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} in a way that is robust to column outliers and missing entries.

However, MCO comes with two issues that might hinder its accuracy. First, it aims to complete inliers and detect outliers simultaneously; doing so can be very challenging and thus error-prone. Second, its convex program can not leverage the inherent non-convexity of the problem. To alleviate these issues, we build upon existing non-convex outlier-robust PCA procedures and propose an alternative to MCO. The alternative proposal detects inliers, completes inliers, and estimates the ground-truth subspace Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} in cascade:

  1. 1.

    (Detect Inliers) We first complete all missing entries of X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} by the value 00, thereby obtaining a complete matrix X~0subscript~ğ‘‹0\tilde{X}_{0}; such matrix X~0subscript~ğ‘‹0\tilde{X}_{0} is sometimes called zero-filled data matrix (Yang etÂ al., 2015; Tsakiris and Vidal, 2018a). Similarly to (7), X~0subscript~ğ‘‹0\tilde{X}_{0} can be partitioned into zero-filled inliers and zero-filled outliers. Then we proceed as if the zero-filled inliers were correct completions of UMC inliers X~insubscript~ğ‘‹in\tilde{X}_{\text{in}} that span the ground-truth space Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}, and run existing outlier-robust PCA methods on X~0subscript~ğ‘‹0\tilde{X}_{0}. Since the missing entries of X~~ğ‘‹\tilde{X} are heuristically filled by zeros, such a subspace estimate might be inaccurate, away from Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}, and thus inadequate for the subsequent recovery task. On the other hand, if we are further given an inlier threshold as a hyper-parameter, then we can obtain an estimated partition of inliers and outliers. In particular, an incomplete point x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j} is classified as an inlier if the distance between its zero-filled version and the estimated subspace is smaller than the inlier threshold; otherwise it is an outlier. Hence, we declare a set of inliers as determined by the partition, and will use these estimated inliers for the sequel.

  2. 2.

    (Complete Inliers) The detected inliers x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j}â€™s in the previous step are in fact incomplete, and at this point, we will no longer rely on their zero-filled versions; instead, we aim to find their authentic completions (xjâˆ—)subscriptsuperscriptğ‘¥ğ‘—(x^{*}_{j})â€™s, which are expected to span Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} if the detected inliers are indeed inliers in the sense of (7). In other words, we are now confronted with a low-rank matrix completion task. Therefore, step 2 is to complete the detected inliers using standard matrix completion algorithms.

  3. 3.

    (Estimate Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}) Finally, given an estimate for the ground-truth rank rğ‘Ÿr, we can now simply perform a singular value decomposition on the matrix of completed inliers, and obtain the final estimate S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} of Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}.

The above routine in cascade can be upgraded into a block coordinate descent method (Peng and Vidal, 2023): Alternate among inlier detection and completion and subspace estimation. Moreover, convergence guarantees of (Peng and Vidal, 2023) might be applied here. That said, we do not pursue this idea of block coordinate descent here, as the above routine already shows satisfactory recovery performance (see Section 4.2).

Stage-II of UMC

After Stage-I, we have obtained an estimate S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} of the ground-truth subspace Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} and completed inliers. Since each outlier x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j} is a point xjâˆ—subscriptsuperscriptğ‘¥ğ‘—x^{*}_{j} in Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} except being permuted and having some entries missing, there is a chance of recovering a good estimate x^jsubscript^ğ‘¥ğ‘—\hat{x}_{j} of xjsubscriptğ‘¥ğ‘—x_{j} from S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} and x~jsubscript~ğ‘¥ğ‘—\tilde{x}_{j}. In such cases, we can first restore the permutation of each column via solving (8) on observed entries (using the subspace PÏ‰jâ€‹S^subscriptğ‘ƒsubscriptğœ”ğ‘—^ğ‘†P_{\omega_{j}}\hat{S}) and then complete the missing entries of that column via a least-squares computation. We summarize our approach in Algorithm 3.

4 Experimental Evaluation

Here we perform synthetic and real data experiments to evaluate the proposed algorithmic pipelines for UPCA (Section 4.1) and UMC (Section 4.2). We use two metrics for performance evaluation. The first is the largest principal angle Î¸maxâ€‹(Sâˆ—,S^)subscriptğœƒsuperscriptğ‘†^ğ‘†\theta_{\max}(S^{*},\hat{S}) between the estimated subspace S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} and ground-truth Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}, and this is used for Stage-I to evaluate subspace learning accuracy. The second metric is the relative estimation error â€–X^âˆ’Xâˆ—â€–Fâ€–Xâˆ—â€–Fsubscriptnorm^ğ‘‹superscriptğ‘‹ğ¹subscriptnormsuperscriptğ‘‹ğ¹\frac{\|\hat{X}-X^{*}\|_{F}}{\|X^{*}\|_{F}} between the estimated data matrix X^^ğ‘‹\hat{X} and the ground-truth Xâˆ—superscriptğ‘‹X^{*}, which quantifies the final performance of our algorithmic pipeline. For both metrics, smaller values imply better performance.

The performance of the other three methods is shown only for their operational regime, where the given data are corrupted by sparse permutations, and Algorithm 2 most accurately captures the illumination of the original image. Overall, we find these results encouraging, especially if one takes into consideration that the methods are very efficient, requiring only 0.2â€‹sâ€‹eâ€‹c0.2ğ‘ ğ‘’ğ‘0.2sec (AIEM), 7â€‹sâ€‹eâ€‹c7ğ‘ ğ‘’ğ‘7sec (â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}-RR), 0.2â€‹sâ€‹eâ€‹c0.2ğ‘ ğ‘’ğ‘0.2sec (PL) and 10â€‹sâ€‹eâ€‹c10ğ‘ ğ‘’ğ‘10sec (Algorithm 2), discounting the DPCP step, which costs 0.1â€‹sâ€‹eâ€‹c0.1ğ‘ ğ‘’ğ‘0.1sec, regardless of permutation type. This is in contrast with existing deep network architectures for visual permutation learning, such as (SantaÂ Cruz etÂ al., 2019), which are based on branch-and-bound and thus have in principle an exponential complexity in the number of permuted patches.

4.2.1 Stage-I of UMC

As discussed in Section 3.2, Stage-I amounts to solving the problem of matrix completion with column outliers, and for this, we can use two approaches. One is MCO (Chen etÂ al., 2015), which simultaneously detects the inliers and estimates the ground-truth subspace Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*}. The other approach, called DPCP+IST, is an instantiation of our idea in Section 3.2: (1) detect the inliers applying the DPCP method (Tsakiris and Vidal, 2018b) on zero-filled data; (2) complete the detected inliers using a non-convex method based on iterative soft thresholding (Majumdar and Ward, 2011), which we call IST; (3) estimate Sâˆ—superscriptğ‘†S^{*} using an SVD on the matrix of completed inliers.

In particular, via Figure 10 we deliver two messages:

  • â€¢

    Both MCO and DPCP+IST find an accurate enough subspace estimate S^^ğ‘†\hat{S} given sufficiently many inliers and observed entries. For example, we have Î¸maxâ€‹(Sâˆ—,S^)subscriptğœƒmaxsuperscriptğ‘†^ğ‘†\theta_{\text{max}}(S^{*},\hat{S}) equal to 2.44âˆ˜superscript2.442.44^{\circ} for MCO and 5.51âˆ˜superscript5.515.51^{\circ} for DPCP+IST for 10%percent1010\% missing entries and 50%percent5050\% outliers.
